Note: ESP32 “pin 1, 2, etc.” aren’t actual PINs; they just mean that you can use any pin if it doesn’t hold another function according to your device’s datasheet (FOR THE PIR MAKE SURE THE PIN SUPPORTS DEEP SLEEP WAKE-UP). 
Similarly, it doesn’t matter what wires you use for the connections to the motor as long as they’re of the same coil.
Additionally, if you’re using a different motor driver, the pin names should still be similar.

As mentioned previously, this build is adapted off of the SolarCat so it uses the same power source
You don't have to use it as long as whatever you use supplies enough power but this tutorial assumes you do. 
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Motor Driver Current Limiting

We NEED to limit the current hitting the motor by setting a Vref value
For the TMC2209, we can calculate the attatched formula:

You can also use this calculator: https://learn.watterott.com/silentstepstick/faq/#calculator-tmc21xx-and-tmc2209 (recommended lol)
For our purposes, 0.99V (~0.7A) should be enough. If your motor isn’t working properly, try setting Vref lower.
You can change Vref by twisting the knob on the TMC2209 with a screwdriver and measuring the current entering across any connection from the driver to the motor (make sure the voltage is plugged in). DO NOT USE THE VREF PIN!!!
The formula is different for different motor drivers if you use them.
